segments.text: We are interviewing Mike Mahoney today at his home in Northeast Dallas.
And Mike, I'd like to have you begin by recalling your first efforts at planning in Texas and then the events that you were connected with that you feel were really significant for Texas.
and for planning education and so forth.

OK. Maybe, Bob, it would be best to back up and explain, because it's hard for me to talk about my planning career in Texas without also talking about the segments in and out of the state which were taking place in Arizona.
I started in the planning office in Tucson, which was then a city county planning office.
in January of 1948.
Worked there under a man by the name of Ed Wilson.
Then in September of 1948, took a job in El Paso as assistant city planning engineer, that strange kind of title.
under Walter E. Stockwell, who was then the planning engineer for the city and had been for many, many years.
I was there until 1950, then in grad school at University of Oklahoma, then went back to Tucson in 1951 and worked again in the city county planning department.
This time, though, under Andre M. Foer,
Andre Melville for.
He was related somehow or other to the famous Melville of Moby Dick.
And Andy was a very forthright, down to earth, school of hard knocks planner who had a very deep sense of appreciation for design, a very deep sense of appreciation for human relations.
Gained a great deal from Andy.
And two years after that,
In 1953, I had the good fortune to be designated as planning director for the city of Austin.
So I was in Austin for the five-year period of 53 to 58.
In 58, the lure of Arizona drew me back, plus some bad health experiences in Austin.
And the doctor said, you better get out.
And I went to Yuma, Arizona as head of the city county planning department.

Small operation, but one that was very satisfying because I was able to work with a community that was really interested in trying to do something following some rather unhappy planning experiences that they had had.
Some people in the city viewing it to be good, and some people in the city and the county viewing it not to be so good.
For two years after that, after those four years, I was in Phoenix as assistant planning director when John Beatty was director.
And then in 1964, became planning director in Fort Worth.
Jerry Brownlee was then city manager.
He was one of LP Cookingham's protgs.
And it was partly because of that influence that I decided to make
the switch and come back to Texas and was in the planning, as head of the planning office for the city of Fort Worth from 64 to 68.
In 68, I left the city, went into private work, and remained in private practice essentially on a very active basis for about six years after that.

However, during that time, then I decided that what I found myself doing was really trying to teach a lot of people in city government and in the community how to push the right buttons, which levers to pull, what doors to open and which doors to close in order for them to accomplish their civic objectives, community objectives.
planning commissions, and boards of adjustment, and library boards, and park and recreation boards, citizen groups, neighborhood associations, and so on.
And that was really kind of a culmination of things that turned me from being the, as much as I liked the design side of planning, I moved very strongly into the community relations side
and went on to pursue a doctorate in adult continuing ed at North Texas.

And then in, let's see, it's been 10 years ago, 11 years ago now, in 1975, took a position at East Texas State University and really became the program director for the graduate program in adult continuing education at East Texas with both master's and doctoral programs.
But all through those 10 years, I have continued to be involved as I was

for roughly 10 years before that in some kind of adjunct types of planning activities, particularly with the Soil Conservation Service, very regularly, once or twice a year for them in their Fort Worth Regional Training Center, which is now their National Training Center.

earlier for Southern Methodist University, teaching through the Department of Real Estate and Regional Science under Sid Reagan, teaching basic course in planning and then one graduate course in public policy and business administration combination.
And before that, at

TCU and the Urban Studies program and along the way at UT Arlington for the fifth year design classes in the School of Architecture and many many years before that as a critic for the University of Texas at Austin in the fifth year design classes in architecture and planning.
So and earlier than that I guess yes when I was in Phoenix I was teaching
for what was then called Phoenix Evening College.
It's now the Maricopa County Community College District and was very much involved there.
Educationally, my interest was really multifaceted because my first degree was in civil engineering from University of New Mexico, then graduate work at both UT Austin
and Oklahoma in city and regional planning.

Then, because of some of my interests on more mundane things of academia, I became one of the key players in designating the site for the Yuma County Community College District's eventual campus of 640 acres.
east side of Yuma, became also instrumental in the locating of the south campus for the Tarrant County Junior College District.
And I've kind of kept my oar in the pond all along on the education side of the ledgers over the years, as well as on the planning side.
Now, where do you want me to back up?
And what do you want me to fill in from all of this?
Well, why don't you go back to your first experience in municipal planning.
That would be in Austin.
And any consultants that were active in Austin at that time?
Well, the earlier ones were really within the state of Texas were really El Paso.
And I think that one was somewhat unusual in that Walter Stockwell,
who was then the planning engineer.
And remember, this was in a period, the latter part of the 40s.
Dan Ponder was then the mayor and very positive, aggressive individual.
The city of El Paso in 1928 had designated or had hired as a consultant

Mr. Kessler and I have a copy of that plan oh you do have okay and the Kessler plan came out of work that Walter Stockwell was very much involved in I think particularly with reference to that there were two things that somewhat stand out as accomplishments over the years since
And some of these have only been accomplished within the last eight or ten years.
One was the construction of a scenic route around Mount Franklin on the north side of downtown El Paso, more or less the north side of El Paso.
And that has become, over the years, pretty much of a shortcut route from the northeast part of El Paso to the northwest part of El Paso.

More significantly, though, quite a few miles further to the north, Walter Stockwell, encouraged, I think, by Mr. Kessler, had worked very strenuously in trying to carry out the one proposal that Kessler made, which I'm sure a lot of people thought was purely pie in the sky.
And that was the building of a road
through the Franklin Mountains, I say through, kind of meandering through the arroyos and the canyons, through an area called McKelligan Canyon.
And that now connects the far north side of El Paso on the east with the far north side of El Paso on the west, a road that is really quite an accomplishment engineering-wise.
It was a route that Kessler had the good sense to see was ultimately going to be needed.
And this was in a day and time when El Paso, as I recall, maybe only had 60,000 people.
And he was looking to the time when it would be 10 times that size and that the need would be very real.
I think that's perhaps the major contribution.
Walter Stockwell's major contribution was his tenacity.
in digging away and pushing for things.
Although he had had some physical health problems over the years, he hung in there very tenaciously like an animal just clawing onto its prey.
And he would not let go.
And he said, we will do these things.
And he would find ways with changes in the mayors who were the actual
administrators of the city, even though they changed political beliefs and so on, he would constantly find a way to convince them to move ahead on projects.
And so I think of the planters in the state probably, although he came from a very different time and a very different orientation, Walter Stockwell probably had in his own unique way as much that
is merited in the way of dedication and accomplishment as any planner in the state.
What was the relationship between Stockwell and Cunningham?
I had left, and John Cunningham came in much later.
I don't know what the relationship was.
I'm sorry, I can't really speak to that.
When I was in Austin from 53 to 58, I went in under a set of circumstances that were very, I think, very beneficial to me and very unusual.
The city of Austin had just then, within a matter of 60 days before, 45 days before, adopted a new city charter.
And for the first time, the city of Boston had a section in its charter devoted to city planning.
And that section of the charter has since been amended once, maybe twice.
But that section of the charter gave a very strong recognition to the role of, as it was designated, the master plan.
gave a very strong responsibility to the Planning Commission to move forward on a master plan for the city.
During the time that I was there, Martin from the School of Architecture at UT was appointed to the Planning Commission.
He was one of the new appointees coming in under the charter
revision, charter reform program.
And really, this charter was a wholesale revamping of the old city charter.
And I mean like 95% of it was a complete redo in concept, in philosophy, in structure, everything.
Walter Sehome was the city manager and the man I reported to.
And you wouldn't.
Yeah, I'm sorry.
Oh, you want to go ahead?
Yeah.
All right.

Immediately following the organization of the Planning Commission under the new charter, I was asked to establish some guidelines for the employment of a planning consultant to help us move quickly on a master plan.
And in the process, we had sent out invitations
to a number of individuals.
Needless to say, we contacted the old faithfuls like Bartholomew and Segoe.
And then we had some others who were not as well known, but in various ways had something to offer us.
I felt city manager was not particularly knowledgeable
By the way, Walter was an electrical engineer by background, came through the electric utility, which was municipally owned.
And so lots of things turned on decisions that really affected the electric utility.
That was the first decision point.
Then after that, then the community came in as the decision point.
So many times, the profit and loss statement in the electric utility controlled a lot of what happened in city government.
Strange.
But normally also the electric utility made lots of money for the city and that was fine, but a lot of the city budget was dependent on that electric utility.

So everything sort of shifted to what is going to be good for the electric utility and if that's good for that element then obviously we're going to make money and therefore that will help underwrite the rest of the operating budget of the city.
Planning being one of those that, of course, was dependent upon the various revenue sources.
In the process, we had the experience of a last minute applicant who had not been contacted by us in the regular process.

through a contact he had made, he just happened to be coming through town, I think, as best I know, he had either been, for some reason, made contact with Hugo Leipziger at UT Austin or Martin Kermesie, and at that point, and there was really within only a matter of four or five days of the closing of the
the bid time or proposal time, we had an 11th hour and 59th minute submittal by Hal Wise.
And looking back, I must say, at the time, I was a little annoyed because I hadn't had a chance to visit with Hal, tell him what the situation was on the ground.
But at the same time,
Looking back, I can also say I was very pleased with the energy that Hal Wise's operation provided us.
That was the plus part of the whole business.
Hal brought in Harry Halliton.
I don't remember which city Harry was in before that.
He also brought in Bruce Weber as a researcher, W-A-Y-B-U-R. Harry G. Halliton, Harry the Horse Halliton, as he was known, was the resident planner.
And he was very effective in organizing a local staff for Halwise.

technician and a couple of people that were employed on an occasional basis and a secretary and then Bruce Weber came in periodically in various parts of the research program Bruce is and I think this may say something about him Bruce's has long since passed away but
kind of a side story.
Bruce was in the service as a translator.
He at that time had a PhD in German and history when he went into the service during World War II.
He was assigned to Patton's unit when they were moving in up the Italian peninsula and he wound up
wherever it was that Patton's headquarters were to be located just before Patton was killed.
And Bruce was assigned to the intelligence unit specifically to gather information on the Krupp interests and the other industrial interests.
One of his jobs was to find out where
the various records were of all these German industrialists, because these were not at the company locations in Germany.
The industrialists saw the handwriting on the wall, they knew that the Allies were soon going to overpower Germany and the Axis, and they spirited their records away to all kinds of places.
Bruce and a couple of other
and he was like a tech sergeant or staff sergeant at that time.

He told this story of having located some of the Krupp records, and it was a whole trunk full of Krupp industrialist records on the third or fourth floor of a house in this small village where they were going through
How he got onto this, I don't know, except by process of just asking people questions about things that had been brought in.

And he and another soldier were carrying this trunk of materials down to their jeep to take it into the intelligence office so that the materials could be gone over piece by piece in preparation for the Nuremberg trials.
And as Bruce said, described the situation as typical in so many European buildings, the stairwells are very narrow.
And he said they were having trouble with this very, very heavy trunk.
And he said it must have weighed 300 pounds, because it was full of paper.
And he said in the process, they made a turn, and they had trouble tipping the trunk so they could carry it down.
And he said, I was the man on the bottom.

of the stairs carrying the trunk down and he said all at once behind me there was this booming voice that cried out something like this soldier you're in my way and Bruce said he turned around and looked and here it was George Patton and he said sir
I'm sorry, I'm in your way, but I don't have anywhere else to go.
And so Patton quizzed him right then and there.
What was he doing there?
Why were they moving this trunk?
He explained what his mission was.
And Patton, at that point, usually with his gloves on and everything, pulled his gloves off and said, here, let me give you a hand.
And he said at that
stage, everything changed.
He said Patton helped them down the next two flights and helped them load the truck on the jeep.
Then proceeded to write out a note.
He took down Waber's name and said, Sergeant Waber, if I can do anything for you, here's an official pass.
You may come to my offices or my tent anytime you need to.

and Bruce said he was so shocked by the whole thing because Patton's reputation of course was always one of being very gruff and pretty demanding of everyone but he said it was a very heartening experience and he said as a matter of fact he did go in a day or two later and he had a drink with Patton and he said Patton

really expressed his appreciation for the work that the intelligence people were doing because he said without that work this is the way he told waver he said without that work we will not be able to win this war so much for the side story bruce was an extremely accomplished researcher and a very good writer you mentioned that he had been he came from marin county
Yes, I think Bruce was, I believe, located at Marin County before he went to work for Hal Wise.
What year are we talking about?
Well, Hal came in in 54, let's see, yes, I guess it was 1954.
To Austin.
To Austin, right.
And Bruce came along just within a matter of,
four weeks behind me.
So this was probably the middle, late spring or middle of 1954.
When Hal Wise came to Austin, I think there was one immediate contribution, and that was that through a series of community meetings,
And there were quite a few of them.
I don't remember the number now, except that there was one like every three or four weeks for probably a period of four or five months, six months.
I remember three questions of how always ask, and you've probably heard these before.
After a presentation of some of the problems and some of the
that the city was having and some of the information that came out of the basic census records and land use records and so on that we already had compiled to some extent.
Hal would always ask people, what do you like most, what do you like least about your city, and what do you want to see changed?
Of course, a very good format of a paradigm for ferreting out public opinion.
But it built, I think,

a lot of people who were very much concerned about the way the city was going and a confidence that our planning effort our comprehensive planning effort would be reasonably successful what came out of the plan it's beyond the plan itself which was as I see it a pretty good document
over the long haul.
In fact, a remarkably good document over the long haul.
And I'm speaking between the mid-1950s and the mid-1980s.
While the plan has been updated, many of the basic concepts that were contained in the planning recommendations, which did involve
involve a very heavy consultant input, but also involve a substantial amount of citizen reflection on those inputs.
A lot of those concepts and principles have been adhered to down through the years since.
One of the initial, or I should say one of the initial, one of the initial issues

the public expressed concern about was the Missouri Pacific Railroad which came down through the west side of Austin north-south alignment to the west side of Austin that route was always a point of contention because to get a full load fully loaded train out of Austin going upgrade
it would usually take about four to six diesel units to pull the train.
And that train could not go more than about 20 miles an hour going up that grade.
In fact, that was, at that time, the steepest grade in the state of Texas for any distance at all.
It was then about a 10-mile grade, and it was the steepest one in the state.
That, of course, as a point of contention for a lot of citizens, resulted in the establishment of the Missouri Pacific Freeway alignment.
So-called Mopac.
The Mopac, right.
Mopac Boulevard, as it's known.
And that now, of course, has been extended way on to what would be called the northwest side of Austin.
15 miles out from downtown.
And also recently to the south.
Yeah, and has been extended to the south now across the Reviton.
The concepts of that particular thing, the whole concept of that corridor was one of the issues.
A second one that Hal did capitalize on
although I think in the years since it has not been preserved quite as well as it should have been, was the very strong commitment to the recreation facilities in Austin.
Beverly Sheffield had been recreation director for the city for a number of years.
He was an aquatics man, a person who believed very strongly in aquatics experiences for kids starting at age five
or four or younger, and he was the instigator of the concept of free neighborhood pools.
That largely came about because sometime during the 1930s, Austin had the drowning of a small youngster in one of the large municipal pools, which was the one down on Riverside.
down next to the river.
